column168: At approximately 1200 noon on Saturday February 9, 2013 tank car BIGX 1019 was reported leaking by public citizen. Upon arrival in the Knoche Yard in Kansas City, MO the tank car was isolated and investigated. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders were activated.    Upon further investigation by emergency responder 3 leaks were found from within both cabinets (right-side + left-side). The first leak source was found in the R side cabinet where the Bottom Fill Valve (V-2) was found slightly open and liquid Argon was leaking out of a gap in the Hose Bleed valve connection. Shipper may have offered this car into transportation with the cracked and leaking Hose Bleed valve.      The second leak was also in the R side cabinet, where the Pressure Build Valve was found slightly open and leaking from the vaporizer. Both of these leaks were caused from loose valves, with loose zip-tie straps which were installed incorrectly.     The third leak was found in the L side cabinet where the regulator valve was found with the adjustment lock nut loose and the adjustment screw was backed out placing the regulator in the open position. All three leak sources were repaired and the tank car released back into transportation. The shipper will secire the One Time Movementa Approval (OTMA).    * No injuries reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.     It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

WHEN MATERIAL REACHED FLUID STATE, PRODUCT BEGAN TO SEEP OUT OF THE DISCHARGE VALVE RESULTING IN A SPILL OF APPROX. 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL ONTO THE PAVEMENT. WHEN LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, DRIVER SHUT VALVE COMPLETELY AND RELEASE STOPPED. THERE WAS NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE, THIS WAS HUMAN ERROR.
column169: DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED IN ALL INSTANCES TO HAVE HOSES PROPERLY CONNECTED PRIOR TO OPENING ANY VALVES.

I received a call from Greg Weber at 10 PM last night stating that he had been placed out of service at the Punta Gorda, FL scale house located at the 159 mile marker on Interstate route 75.    Greg stated that they had discovered a small leak on the trailer he was using. The trailer number is  719 and its in nice condition. Greg was trying to explain to me where it was leaking but he finally put the DOT inspector on and the inspector and I had a good conversation and he was able to explain the situation better. It was reported by the inspector that there was a small barely audible leak coming from the internal valve area. Upon further discussion with the inspector, he was finally able to pin point the leak to the 3 bolt shaft and cam housing that bolts into the side of the internal valve. On some valves, there is an O ring inserted in the housing, on others it’s a thin metal gasket. The inspector had used a “soap” solution to pin point the leak.    The next step then was that I called ARI and had them send out a service truck and I had them snug down on the 3 bolts on the housing slightly and they were able to get the leak to where it was not apparent enough to keep the inspector from releasing the unit. This is not a normal step to take as those bolts never loosen up but we had nothing to lose at this point. Snugging those bolts just that little extra closed the gap on the defective gasket just enough to slow it down to an occasional bubble.    The trailer is to be unloaded at Naples and then taken directly into Krutsingers repair services in Tampa.

column168: On February 7, 2013, at 1725 hours, an FRA Inspector at the CSX Hawthorn Yard, Indianapolis, IN., took exception to tank car GATX 6677, a loaded tank car of UN1830, Sulfuric Acid, due to a blown rupture disc. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Southern States, C/O Savannah Acid Plant, was notified via Chemtrec report #2013020700247. Summit, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the appropriate 165 pound rupture disc in place and ruptured. The shipper representative, Bryan Beyer 912-232-1101, cell 912-313-0998, was notified of the condition found. The rupture disc was replaced, the pressure relief device housing was secured and GATX 6677 was released for disposition.    This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 2(5+5+1)x(2+0) = 44  Cause Code: 441
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On February 9, 2013 at 11:05 hours, personnel in the CSX Rocky Mount Yard discovered GATX 22936, a residue tank car of Flammable Liquid N.O.S., emitting vapors from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Renessenz LLC was notified via CHEMTREC report #2013-02-09-00036. HEPACO, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release to be a misaligned and damaged manway cover gasket.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Renessenz representative, Brenda Murray at 314-393-3443.  HEPACOs response team installed a new gasket and properly secured the manway cover for transportation.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 220   NARRI: 5(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50

column168: CN transportation department employee noted an odor coming from tank car UTLX 85951 (Residue / Acetic Acid, UN2789) during switching operations at the CN Joliet Yard, Joliet, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the manway gasket misaligned and protruding out the side of the manway. All swing bolts were less than tool tight. Manway gasket was realigned and all swing bolts were secured. Shipping plugs for the liquid and vapor valves secured also. Seal applied to manway and combination housing. Tank car was released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Car was noticed hissing and with an ice ball around the port in the protective housing through which the regulator valve discharge pipe extended.  Contractor called to respond.  Contractor opened protective housing cover and found the discharge pipe from the regulator to the outside of the protective housing was loose at the regulator, allowing CO2 to discharge inside the housing, filling the housing with frost and and freezing the regulator valve open.  Contractor defrosted the interior of the protective housing and the regulator and waited for it to reset.  Once the regulator reset they removed the pipe, brushed it out, taped the threads and resecured with a wrench.  Shipper has been notified of problem and car will be shopped after unloading.  Car was released back into transporation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank Car PLMX 135473 was noticed with ice around protective housing while being humped.  Car was isolated and NS Enviromental and a contractor was called to respond and heard hissing coming from the protective housing.  Contractor metered the car and detected flammable gas readings.  There were no seals on the protective housing cover so they opened the housing.  Examination revealed one of the vapor valves was open and the plug was loose onthe valve.  Contractor closed the valve about a 1/4 turn,and tightened the plug 3 turns before it was wrench tight.  Car released back into transporation.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, the driver blacked out, which resulted in a vehicle accident.  The driver side saddle tank was damaged, as a result of the accident, which caused the release of approximately 50 gallons of diesel fuel.  The trailer was hauling hazmat cargo at the time of the accident, which resulted in damage to the freight inside the trailer.  Thirteen (13) 55-gallon drums, which contained NA 3077, hazardous waste solid, n.o.s. (lead contaminated debris), were damaged.  Eight (8) drums were overpacked without further incident.  Five (5) drums were severely damaged, releasing their contents to the concrete surface beneath trailer.  Master Environmental of Meridian, Idaho was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Master Environmental overpacked the eight (8) remaining drums, and proceeded to recover all free product and debris from the affected areas.  There was no impact to surface soils or threat to enter state waters.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Rinchem Company, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: At 1630 hours on February 2, 2013, Train Q47802 derailed nine (9) cars near mile post 310.1 on the Wilmington Subdivision.  Tank car UTLX206596, residue - N Propanol, was derailed and de-trucked and came to rest off the track structure at the 170 degree position.  As a result of the impact with adjacent heavy brush and trees, the liquid and vapor line valves sheared off the pressure plate assembly.  During the process of uprighting the container, the car pivoted resulting in the loss of 2 gallons of product from the shared off valves. The local fire department enacted an evacuation due to the proximity of homes to the derailment site.       ATARI  5(5+1) (2+4)= 180

column168: Contractor was transfering material from tank car to tank truck and had "emptied" TILX 196927.  When they moved the pump to the next tank car they left the unloading line connected to the bottom outlet of TILX 196927 and neglected to close the bottom outlet valve on the tank car.  The strain on the unloading hose broke the aluminum fitting attached to the bottom outlet which allowed the residue from the tank car to drain out, along with the material left in the unloading hose and pump.  Approximately 50 gallons were caught in the spill pan and the remainder fell into the containment area.  Material in containment area evaporated before clean up contractor arrived.  Spill area was pressure washed and rinsate collected.  Material captured in spill pan was pumped back into the tank truck.

column168: • Thomas Moore and Britton Nystrom completed loading a truck at this pump location at 4:30 pm.  Thomas and Britton were waiting for another truck to arrive when they decided to start taking down another loading location that was finished for the day. Thomas Moore said he was taking the golf cart to pick up a hose and other equipment.  Without checking anything he jumps into the golf cart and pulls forward not realizing that it was attached to the pump.  The pump and hose were still connected to the railcar waiting for the next load.  In pulling forward he pulled the pump and hose which resulted in the bottom railcar outlet coupling being snapped spilling an estimated 100 gallons of which 50 gallons where caught by the pan.
column169: Operating procedures were immediately changed. Vehicles used to move pump carts from one railcar to another must be disconnected from the pump cart before set-up continues and the vehicle must be removed from the containment area. In addition, the trailer hitch for the pump carts has a keyed lock that requires management to unlock before the vehicle can be attached to the pump for movement. This allows management to verify the SOP for pump movement has been correctly followed.

column168: The transload employee at Birmingham TRANSFLO was conducting a tank car to truck trailer transfer of Methylene Diphenyl Isocyanate(MDI) on 2/1/2013. The loader was to load 45,000 lbs on the trailer.  He had checked the load gauge at 8,000 lbs, but did not go back up the loading platform and check the volume on the load until the gauge was at zero. He followed normal procedure and blew the loading line empty.  He unhooked the lines per the procedure.  As he started down the platform he noticed that 3 gallons of MDI had released when he blew the line clean. The release occured when the line was blown clean after excess product build up in the loading line. The area was barricaded off and all spilled MDI was contained. No drains, water, or soil were impacted. Material was cleaned up and placed into a 55 gallon container.
column169: DIRECT CAUSES:   Lack of situational awareness – Employee failed to monitor the transfer as instructed in SSP 3025-026 “Transferring MDI with Air Compressor”.  He checked the gauge at 8,000 lbs. and did not check it again until it was already at zero.       ROOT CAUSES:   1. Failure to check and monitor – Employee did not watch the pressure gauge often enough.   He should have stopped the transfer before the gauge was at zero pressure.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1. Personal Communication – Review transloading task instruction with all terminal employees.  – Completed 2/11/2013  2. Materials and Service Management – Procurement of goods.  Working with TRANSFLO to determine if a high level alarm should be used on all transfers of MDI.

column168: Approximately 35 gallons of product was released from a 55-gallon drum due to a load shift during transit. The released material impacted the trailer floor and parking lot below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup.

This incident occurred during the unloading process.  Steve Arthur Foster driver was unloading diesel fuel into a stationary above ground tank.  All hoses were connected and the unloading was taking place.  The coupling connection at the above groung tank disconnected due to vibration from the PTO on the road tractor.  Driver Arthur was in attendance and immediately shut down the unloading procedure.  Total time of release was less than one minute.  Release occurred on a packed down dirt parking lot at a rock quarry.  The release was contained with the help of the quarry utilizing a front end loader and rock dirt to mitigate the spillage.  Examination of the coupling hose indicated wear at the coupling point.  Product did not reach any type of public or natural waterway.
column169: Driver Arthur is trained in the loading and unloading procedures at Foster Fuels, and has unloaded at this facility in the past.  In this particular delivery, we found the coupling connection indicated wear and no velcro fastening strips were used to keep the ears of the coupling connection secure.  This PTO on the road tractor had excessive vibration and has been service.  Velcro fastening strips have been ordered for all Foster Fuels connection hoses.  Foster Fuels will continue to provide training to all of its HM employees and will use this incident for training purposes and safety meetings.   This incident will be made a part of driver Steve Arthur's employment record at Foster Fuels Inc.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector reported observing tank car UTLX 65941 standing on the interchange track with dried commodity residue spillage on its tank shell and around it manway closure. The leak source appeared to be from the threaded vacuum relief valve (VRV) mounted atop the manway lid. Contract responders inspected the VRV and reported finding the pressure seal at the bottom of the VRV was out of position and pinched, thus not sealing or allowing the VRV to fully close. This condition allowed commodity to be expelled from under the VRV's top weather cap during movement. The responders applied and secured a steel pipe plug in the vacated VRV orifice. Spillage on UTLX 65941 was neutralized and water rinsed. No ground impact from spillage was observed.

column168: Tank car GATX 202260 was observed leaking commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard. A catch receptacle was placed under GATX 202260 to contain the side shell commodity drips. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder reduced the internal pressure within GATX 202260. Responder's inspection revealed that the liquid valve was in an open position and the leak source appeared to be from the valve stem. The liquid valve was closed which ended any further commodity release. The responder noted that the liquid valve's operating handle came in contact with the valve housing cover's inner sidewall when the housing cover was closed. This contact forced the valve's operating handle to move to an open position. The responder removed the operating handle and placed it atop the fitting plate within the valve housing area. The liquid valve's packing gland nut at the valve stem was tight. The valve housing cover was then closed and pinned.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all vales and fittings.

column168: Tank car DBUX 250779 was reported sloshing commodity from its manway closure during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected DBUX 250779. No commodity impacted the ground and evaporating spillage was confined to DBUX 250779's side shell and manway nozzle area. DBUX 250779 deemed safe to move was isolated in the railyard for a detailed inspection.  Further inspection revealed that one of the six manway securement bolts was not tool tight. The manway cover was opened to inspect the product outage level and the manway gasket condition. The product outage was deemed appropriate. The applied manway gasket was intact and no apparent defects were noted. A new manway gasket was applied to ensure a good seal when the manway lid was properly secured. The manway lid was closed and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened.

column168: On February 8, 2013 at approximately 1620, an employee at the Tampa TRANSFLO terminal was performing railcar arrival inspection on railcar # PPRX 28503. At the time the employee observed product leaking (hexane) from dome lid and pressure relief device (PRD). He immediately reported the leak to the TRANSFLO terminal manager. Employee tightened dome lid which secured the leak from that area, however, product continued to flow from the relief device. Spill pans were placed in track pans under railcar to catch the liquid hexane that was being released. Once the Terminal Manager determined that leak could not be stopped by tightning the dome lid bolts, all terminal personnell were evacuated and the fire department was called.  Hillsborough County Fire Rescue responded. Approximately 5 ½ gallons released and were captured in the spill pans. No other environmental impacts resulted. With the Fire Department present, 2000 lbs gallons of hexane was transloaded from the railcar to a truck trailer which reduced pressure on the railcar and eliminated the release of additional product.     AWARENESS ITEMS:   1. Railcar arrived 07 February 2013 on the morning switch.  2. Railcar capacity is 29,918 gallons; Railcar Shipping Paper listed 28,290 gallons.  3. Ambient temperature in Tampa on 2/8/2013 was 85 degrees F.  4. Product expands as ambient temperature increases.  5. Pressure releif device was set at 75 psi.    IMMEDIATE / DIRECT CAUSE:  1. Temperature Extremes - Product expanded in railcar resulting in the release of the pressure relief device and subsequent product release.      BASIC ROOT CAUSE:  1. Railcar was overloaded at load port.  Railcar headspace was only 1,628 gallons. Temperature extremes were not taken into account during railcar loading.
column169: IMMEDIATE / DIRECT CAUSE:  1. Temperature Extremes - Product expanded in railcar resulting in the release of the pressure relief device and subsequent product release.      BASIC ROOT CAUSE:  1. Inadequate assessment of need and risks - Railcar was overloaded at load port.  Railcar headspace was only 1,628 gallons. Temperature extremes were not taken into account during railcar loading.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1. Tighten dome lid to secure release from the dome lid.-COMPLETED 2/8/2013  2. Off-loaded 2000 gallons of product which reduce pressure on railcar and stopped the product from leaking from the pressure relief device.- COMPLETED 2/8/2013

column168: Tank car GATX 80166 was reported with a commodity leak emanating from its manway closure during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a BNSF mechanical inspection deemed GATX 80166 safe to move to a nearby repair track in the railyard. No additional commodity release was observed when GATX 80166 remained motionless. A BNSF hazardous material responder inspected GATX 80166 in the early daylight hours on 2/11/2013. The responder reported all shipper seals intact, all six manway securement bolts tool tight and spillage on the side shell was evaporating. The manway was opened to inspect the gasket condition which revealed two manway gaskets applied. A manway nozzle gasket was installed around the top of the manway nozzle and a manway cover gasket was applied in the manway gasket slot at the underside of the manway lid. The responder concluded that the two gasket interface did not provide a good closure seal. The gasket under the manway lid was removed and the manway was properly resecured. Also, the liquid valve's operating handle was found in an open position which allowed it to fit under the closed valve housing cover. The liquid valve was closed and the operating handle realigned to enable it to fit under the valve housing cover in the closed position.  All other valves and fittings were found secure. BNSF seals were applied to the manway closure and the valve housing cover. No further commodity release was reported during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car UTLX 200248 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no additional spillage was noted when UTLX 200248 remained motionless. UTLX 200248 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from contract responders. Responders reported 1 of 8 manway securement swing bolts were loose. The manway lid was opened to inspect the manway gasket condition and when opened, the applied manway gasket was out of position and partially fell into the inner manway nozzle area. Also, the manway gasket was crimped and cut in one area. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and all manway securement swing bolts/nuts were properly tool tightened. Securement was completed by 2030 hrs. CST, 2/16/2013. The spillage on UTLX 200248's shell was sprayed with a solution of Micro-Blaze. No ground impact from spillage was observed. Intact shipper seals were replaced by seals numbered 652673 and 652614.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop so as to conduct a load check.  During the load check it was discovered that a small crack was visible at the top of the IBC and a small amount of liquid had splashed from the package. Facility personnel assembled a response team to entered the trailer and address the source of the leak.  The crew proceeded to re-containerize the contents of the leaking container along with all debris and clean-up supplies used to contain the release. At the conclusion of the response activities, the material was placed back on the trailer and was sent to the intended waste management facility where it was accepted and processed without incident.
column169: .      At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of cracking, leaking, or staining was observed that would have indicated a small crack would occur while in transit.  CHES personnel have been advised to continually be diligent in their inspection of containers prior to loading and transporting.

column168: Tank car UTLX 15018 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area in the railyard. Contract responders found the liquid eduction line pipe cap gasket damaged and not sealing, possibly from over-compression when this pipe cap or closure cap was tool tightened. The gasket was replaced and the closure cap was secured by 2330 hrs. CST, 2/13/2013. Spillage on UTLX 15018 was neutralized and wiped. Ground impact spillage under UTLX 15018 was neutralized. Intact shipper seal 149738 was replaced by seals CHV 203411 and CHV 203413.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting rail cars in the railyard; reported tank car BNSF 880375 with commodity wetness around this tank car's bottom outlet valve (BOV). The FRA Inspector also related that the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod could easily be turned by hand and in an open position. The TOBOV packing glad nut ( PGN) was tight and insufficient packing material around the operating rod was thought to be the cause of the loose operating rod. After notification by the FRA Inspector, a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected BNSF 880375. The responder moved the TOBOV operating rod to its closed position and tool tightened the PGN to stabilize the operating rod in its closed position. The BOV's closure cap (BOC) was inspected and reported tight. The commodity drips at the BOV were observed at less than one drip per hour. BNSF 880375 was moved and placed over containment for immediate unloading.  After unloading BNSF 880375 and its BOV drained of all commodity; BNSF 880375 was monitored and no further commodity drips or commodity dampness were observed at the BOV area.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 02/21/2013 at 18:00 hours, CSXT train B73921, a local industry switcher was departing West Springfield Yard on track four main when the rear two tank cars derailed.  ETCX 630541. a loaded UN1129, Butyraldehyde, class 3 flammable liquid was upright and both truck sets derailed.  TILX 191564, a residue UN1173, last contained Ethyl Acetate, was derailed off both truck sets.  No release of product was found during the investigation or re-railing process. Due to the location of the incident, milepost QB98.89 at the overhead bridge of State Route 5, the roadway was closed at 18:15 hours on 02/21/2013 and re-opened at 21:15 hours on 02/22/2013.     During the re-railing process of the tank cars, the West Springfield Fire Chief ordered a mandatory evacuation at 10:00 hours on 02/22/2013.  This evacuation consisted of homes near the derailment site and streets included were Railroad Street, Globe Street, and Bridge Street, consisting of 36 residences and 86 people.  The evacuation was lifted at 17:35 hours and State Route 5 was re-opened at 21:15 hours.    ETCX 630541 and TILX 191564 were re-railed and moved to West Springfield Yard for further inspections.

column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to coordinate a response to a UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance(Dichlorotoluene) release.  ERTS dispatched B&P Enterprises to the site to perform cleanup.  B&P personnel unloaded the trailer and discovered the leaking drum. The drum appeared to be punctured by another pallet.  The contractor over packed the damaged container and left it on the trailer to go back to the shipper for reclamation/disposition. The contractor utilized absorbent pads to collect the released material on the trailer floor.  B&P personnel then hand excavated the impacted gravel below the trailer. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

column168: Local operating manager reported an odor emitting from tank car DUPX 29221.  Inspection of car revealed the vacuum relief valve stuck in the open position and releasing vapor.  Mgr. Lerch was able to operate the valve allowing it to close and secure the car from vapor release. column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves and fittings are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of product while car is in transportation.

column168: During routine yard inspections, UTLX 212359 was found with product on the top and sides of the car.  Inspection of the car found that 2 of 8 manway swing bolts were less than tool tight allowing approximately 3 gallons of product to release from the car.  The seal was removed, the manway opened, and the gasket assessed.  The gasket was in good condition and the manway closed, properly secured, and resealed.  The sides of the car were wiped and the car released back into transportation.

column168: Product was reported to be leaking from within container UMXU 251138.  Inspection of container revealed 4-55 gallon barrels loaded onto a single pallet and banded together. The spill was remediated, and container was released for transportation.  Cause of the release was due to the drum rubbing against lading within the container.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM. PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted an odor coming from tank car WCHX 23126 (Residue / Flammable Liquid N.O.S. - Pulp Mill Liquid) during an inspection at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, IN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting all closures were closed and seals intact. The odor appeared to be coming from the pressure relief device. Air monitoring affirmed that the pressure relief valve was leaking. Swing bolts on the manway were checked for tightness and found to be tool tight. Tank car was held for corrective measures to the pressure relief device by the car owner.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: CN transportation department employee reported a strong odor coming from tank car UTLX 647515 (R/ ACRYLIC ACID, STABILIZED) during switching operations at the CN Fulton Yard, Fulton, KY. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting shipper's seal (LUBRIZOL 004997) protecting the valve housing cover. Further inspection revealed that both plugs to the liquid and vapor valves less than tool tight and the valves partially open. Valves closed, plugs tightened and the odor stopped. Housing cover closed and seal applied, tank car released to shipper for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A citizen notified BNSF that an entrained tank car in a BNSF train was leaking commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area with its bottom outlet cap (BOC) not applied and hanging from its retaining chain. The suspect BNSF train was stopped on main track and a train crew member inspecting the train found entrained tank car TILX 190930 leaking commodity. The BOV operating handle was in an open position and it was closed ending any further commodity release by 1300 hrs. CST 2/17/2013.  Afterwards BNSF and contract responders reported that the BOV operating handle securement pin was sheared-off which allowed the operating handle to fall to an open position and partially opened the BOV. TILX 190930 was set-out of train at a nearby side track.  The BOC was applied and tool tightened. A suitable securement pin was applied to maintain the BOV operating handle in its closed position. Responders measured the product outage at the manway entry of TILX 190930 to determine how much commodity may have been lost. Responders also inspected the right-of-way in length and no commodity pooling or any significant ground spillage was observed or found.

column168: Residue tank car UTLX 67865 was reported emanating a commodity odor in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting UTLX 67865 reported finding the manway securement bolts tight, but the applied manway gasket was pinched and misaligned. Also, the vacuum relief valve (VRV) mounted atop the manway lid was stuck in an open position due to the O-ring under the vent cap being torn and out of position, thus preventing closure. Responders applied a new manway gasket and a new O-ring under the VRV cap. The manway lid was then closed and properly secured. Afterwards, the commodity odor dissipated.

Transloading employee at Birmingham TRANSFLO terminal was breaking down an MDI railcar to truck transfer when the fitting he was turning with the wrench came loose and the valve handle struck the temperature probe valve. This caused the product valve to crack open releasing about 5 gallons of product. No drains or soil were impacted from the 5 gallon release. Employee announced a release on the radio and Product was contained by damming and diking by other terminal employees. Spill was completely cleaned up. No soil or drains impacted.      Cause: Fitting came loose allowing product valve handle to strike against valve handle on temperature probe fitting. Inadaquate lighting caused the employee to not see that the second pipe wrench had fallen off.
column169: Remedial Actions Taken:   Communication to TRANSFLO to increase lighting in the MDI transfer area. Request was made on 3/15/2013.

column168: While conducting a railcar to truck trailer transfer of denatured ethanol on 2/13/2013 at the Norfolk-Southern TBT terminal in Roanoke, VA, a small leak of ethanol was discovered on the asphalt by the transloading employee. 2-3 ounces of denatured ethanol were released onto the pavement due to a seal failure on the lid of the strainer basket on the ethanol transloading pump while unloading railcar UTLX 208399. There was a small cut in the o-ring upon inspection. Seal was changed on the strainer basket. Previous inspections of the lid seal did no reveal any damage to the seal on the strainer basket lid. All ethanol was contained and cleaned up. No soil or water impacted.
column169: Lid seal on the strainer basket of the ethanol pump failed during operation. Employee did not find any defect during previous inspection of the lid seal.     Corrective Action Taken: All employees have been shown the damaged seal and have been instructed what to visually inspect for.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: After being unloaded and released by the consignee (CHS Inc. - Cenex Pipeline Terminal), residue tank car UTLX 204368 was reported to BNSF that it was dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). A BNSF mechanical responder inspected UTLX 204368 and reported residue commodity dripping from the four inch BOV's valve stem. A receptacle was placed under UTLX 204368 to catch drippage. The BOV was cycled open-closed and commodity drips continued. UTLX 204368 was carefully moved and placed over track pan containment. A response contractor cleaned and purged remaining hazardous material from UTLX 204368 without further incident on 2/25/2013. Afterwards, UTLX 204368 was directed to an UTC repair facility.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car UTLX 209787 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 209787 and reported commodity drips emanating from the closed four inch BOV's valve stem. The BOV's valve stem's packing gland nut (PGN) was tightened and the BOV cycled open-closed. The commodity drips ebbed, but continued. UTLX 209787 was cordoned off in the railyard with a catch receptacle placed under UTLX 209787's BOV. The commodity within UTLX 209787 was transferred into tank trucks on 2/21-22/2013 with the BOV completely drained of commodity. Afterwards, no further commodity drips from the BOV were observed. All spillage evaporated. On 3/11/2013, an UTC Mobile Repair crew completed repairs to the BOV and pressure tested UTLX 209787.  The UTC responders reported the BOV ball valve's lower or bottom Teflon gasket had a small nick in it that allowed commodity to bypass the closed valve and escape via the valve stem.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: I APPROACHED THE INCIDENT WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE INCLUDING SILVER SHIELD GLOVES. THE BOX WAS @ HIGH VOLUME POSITION ON PD3 WITH SMALL PUDDLE AROUND IT. NO APPARENT CAUSE FOR DAMAGE. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Train 380 entering yard reported a "fishy" odor when passing track DI10.  All employees in yard were kept out of a 330 foot radius of all the cars in that track.  CHEMTREC, NS Environmental, and Dupont were notified.  This is the servicing yard for Dupont's Belle, WV plant and they voluntarily sent two responders to investigate.  Using an SO2 bottle Dupont found vapors leaking from the protective housing of DUPX 28166.  Dupont opened the protective housing and found a vapor line valve leaking due to not being completely closed and the plug in the valve being less than less than wrench tight.  Dupont closed the valve, removed the plug, cleaned and taped the threads and reapplied the plug with a wrench.  After repairs they tested the all the valves in the housing and found no further leaks.

column168: Tank car PROX 14168 was reported leaking commodity in the railyard. BNSF mechanical /hazardous material responders reduced the internal pressure within PROX 14168 which stopped the slow commodity release. During this process, intact shipper seals NorFalco 123972 and 125241 were removed. Spillage on PROX 14168's shell was neutralized. Observed drippings on the ground under PROX 14168 were also neutralized. PROX 14168 was isolated and cordoned off in the railyard. On 2/25/2013, BNSF contract responders inspecting PROX 14168 reported finding the liquid line's closure cap less than tool tight and the cap gasket missing. A Teflon gasket was installed inside the closure cap and the cap was tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Response was concluded by 1730 hrs. MST, 2/25/2013. On 2/26/2013, the same response contractors decontaminated and cleaned all spillage from PROX 14168.  Responders also pressurized PROX 14168 up to 14 psig with no commodity leaks detected. New seals SRS 000112, 000115 and 000118 were applied to the fill hole, liquid line and air/vapor line respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: CTMV was loaded with material for shipment to waste facility. Pre load inspection of components showed no issue. Loading was completed without any issues. Carrier entered Dow Corning premises and connected to trailer for transport to waste facility. Upon arriving at the main exit gate of Dow Corning a final inspection of the cargo tankrevealed a small wisp of vapor coming from the manway gasket on top of the CTMV. Loading building was contacted and driver was instructed to return the CTMV to the loading station. Container was vented down and loading personnel with assistance of site loss prevention team donned proper PPE and replaced the manway gasket as a precaution verses tightening. Container was pressurized and leak checked prior to continuing it departure. Total quantity released was 1 lb. Material was being shipped under EPA manifest # 010363865JJK. This CTMV is indedicated service.
column169: Corrective actions: Loading personnel and building management reviewed the incident. Future CTMV will be leak checked prior to loading to ensure the manway is leak tight.

column25: Renewable Products Marketing Group Inc. by Dakota Ethanol
column168: Tank car UTLX 208138 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure in the railyard. Contract responders inspected UTLX 208138 and reported finding 2 of 8 manway securement swing bolt nuts less than tool tight. Intact shipper seal TBS 004168 at the manway closure was removed to inspect the condition of the manway gasket. The manway gasket was found intact and serviceable. The manway was then closed and all manway securement bolt nuts properly tool tightened with new seal 768495 applied. All valves and other fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seal TBS 004167 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal 768499. Most spillage evaporated and no indications of ground impact from any escaping commodity were noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and valiidated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 02/23/2013, at 2302 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Winston Terminal discovered CGTX 26044, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Oil, leaking from the liquid line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Noble Oil, Florida State Watch Office, report number 2013-1049 and the NRC were notified. CHEMTREC report # 2013-02-23-00088. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve was in the open position and the secondary securement plug was not applied. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel closed the liquid line valve, reapplied the secondary securement plug and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:119  NARRI:5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: UNITED VISION LOGISTICS, LLC. TRUCK #03275 DRIVEN BY RONALD PERONI LOADED IN BELLE CHASSE, LA. WITH OIL FIELD EQUIPMENT HEADED TO PORT FOURCHON, LA. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CROSS A PONTOON BRIDGE AT THE INTERSECTION OF LA HWY 1 AND LA HWY 308. UPON DRIVING ONTO THE BRIDGE THE FUEL TANKS BOTTOMED OUT AND CAUSED THE DIESEL TANKS TO RUPTURE AND BEGIN TO LEAK DIESEL. THE DRIVER TOOK EVASIVE ACTION AND DROVE OFF OF THE BRIDGE AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE TO MINIMIZE SPILLAGE INTO THE BAYOU. APPOXIMATELY LESS THAN 10 GALLONS WAS SPILLED INTO THE BAYOU. APPOXIMATELY 200 PLUS GALLONS WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND A ROADSIDE DITCH.                        TRIAD ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO CEAN UP THE DIESEL SPILL. LOUISIANA STATE POLICE RIGHT TO KNOW WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT REPORT #13-00876. LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

column168: Martin Transport was dispatched to pick up an empty portable diesel tank on skids at a customer location. Driver was in the process of loading the tank onto the flatbed trailer. A ball valve located on the lower portion of the end of the tank came in contact with the trailer and broke off. Approximately 20 gallons of residue diesel spilled onto the ground. Approximately 1 gallon of diesel flowed into a canal near the tank. Driver constructed a dike to prevent further contamination to the water, and contain the diesel. US Environmental Services was called to clean up the diesel spill on land and water. Booms and absorbent pads were deployed to the water and the sheen was removed.
column169: In the future, have two persons in attendance when loading a portable tank onto a flatbed. One to work the winch controls, and one to watch the actual tank being loaded.

column168: Vehicle 1 (Western Refining Tank vehicle) was traveling north on Highway 285 and it began snowing very  hard with zero visibility. Driver slowed and soon felt an impact and stopped. Unable to see anything outside of the cab the driver opened driver door to assess what occurred. Vehicle 1 was a truck mounted cargo tank - pull cargo tank trailer combination. The pull trailer jack knifed against the truck and punctured the Trailers cargo tank shell. The hole in the tank shell was 12" X 12" located 18" from the bottom of the shell on compartment number 1 of 3 compartments. 1672 gallons of 1800 gallons loaded in compartment 1 leaked onto the roadway and followed the slope of the roqadway aprox 750 feet and flowed into a stormwater drain and into a dry runnoff area. The remainder of the contents of the cargo tank trailer was pumped off onto another cargo tank truck without incident.Vehicle 2 (passenger car) had made contact with the right side of the pull trailer. Vehicle 2 sustained minor damage to the left driver door and hood area. The driver of vehicle 2 was observed and released at the scene of the accident with minor neck pain.Remediation efforts started at 0900 hrs on 02/25/13. Comtaminated soil was excavated and deposited into rolloff bins and relocated to a certified Landfill. New Mexico Department of Transportation and New Mexico Environmental Department have been involved in the remediation process from the begining.
column169: Western has adopted a policy to stop our trucks during winter storms in an effort to eliminate accidents such as this one. We covered adverse driving conditions during our safety meetings at all terminals. We also started post incident remedial training on employees who have incidents or crashes.

column168: After an empty covered hopper stalled on the hump downgrade, a loaded gondola followed and exited group retarders at a high rate of speed and coupled into this empty covered hopper. This high speed coupling knocked the covered hopper off center, elevating its north coupler. A loaded tank car of grease followed and coupled into the loaded gondola also at high rate of speed. These three rail cars continued into the bowl tracks towards motionless BNSF 880247. The covered hopper's elevated coupler struck the lower center of the B-end tank head of BNSF 880247 puncturing it. The cause of the automatic retarder's failure to slow rail cars was attributed to foreign material on the wheels of the humped rail cars. The puncture hole in BNSF 880247's B-end tank head was approximately 2 feet by 3 feet in size and allowed residue commodity to escape from this breach during the movement momentum following the coupling impact. BNSF 880247 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged of hazardous material on 3/7/2013. The ground spillage trail between the rails is scheduled to be treated with a Micro-Blaze solution once warmer ambient temperatures permit.

column168: On Saturday, February 16, 2013, at approximately 06:36, an Air Liquide Industrial (ALIUS) Bulk Driver departed the ALIUS West Point, VA facility in tractor #90650 and trailer #46527 loaded with Oxygen, Refrigerated Liquid (UN 1073) to deliver to a customer site. (See attached for complete answer.)
column169: As of 3/16/13, the accident is still under investigation and corrective actions have yet to be determined, however Air Liquide Industrial has taken immediate steps to prevent reoccurrence to include: Conducting a Safety Stand down and discussing with all employees the importance of continuing to follow the cryogenic products delivery procedure, and the hazards of working with Liquid Oxygen. Ensuring that the Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) and tools they use to perform the task are dean and free of grease, oil, and contaminants. We are also in contact with the other major Industrial Gas companies through the Compressed Gas Association (CGA) regarding the incident and will work with them to prevent a reoccurrence of this type of incident in our industry.

column168: THE DRIVER NOTICE A SMALL DRIP OF RED INK COMING FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER DURING AN INSPECTION WHILE IN TRANSIT. A TEAM WAS CALLED OUT TO INSPECT AND CLEAN THE TRAILER. THE TEAM FOUND 2 5-GALLON PAILS OF YELLOW PRINTING INK LEAKING AND 4 5-GALLON PAILS OF RED PRINTING INK LEAKING. THE TEAM STATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF INK WAS RELEASED FROM THE 6 CONTAINERS. THE TEAM OVER PACKED THE PAILS AND WIPED CLEAN THE IMPACTED PALLETS AND CONTAINERS. THE TEAM ALSO CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR LEAVING A THIN LAYER OF ABSORBENT TO CATCH ANY RESIDUE MISSED. THE LOAD WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO A TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS INSPECTED AND RELOADED. THE DAMAGED TO THE 5 GALLON PAILS ARE BELIEVED TO BEEN CAUSED BY A FORK LIFT WHEN LOADING AND BY PUSHING THE MATERIAL IN TO TIGHTLY CAUSING THEM TO BE CRUSHED AND DENTED. IF FURTHER INFORMATION IS NEEDED PLEASE CONTACT MATT GIRARD AT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AT 405-282-8510 OR MGIRARD@EMIOK.COM

column168: Approximately 73 bbls. of crude oil was released to a County Roadway ditch when a Plains' driver pulled to the left to allow room for an oncoming driver resulting in the collapse of the road shoulder. The collapse of the shoulder caused the tanker to enter the road ditch and roll onto its side where a stone punctured the transport hull. The driver immediately diverted the released liquid away from a nearby stream ditch with onboard response equipment. A secondary transport was mobilized to the site and collected approximately 21 bbls. of product. Response crews collected and additional 5 bbls. of free liquid and aerated and stabilized the impacted soils.
column169: Due to the circumstances of the truck/trailer roll over there is no way to prevent a recurrence.

column168: THE TRACTOR/TANK TRAILER HAD DEPARTED THE TRUCK TERMINAL IN E. ST. LOUIS, IL AND WAS ENROUTE ON I-64 TRAVELING EAST. THE DRIVER NOTICED SOMETHING IN HIS SIDE REAR VIEW MIRROR THAT LOOKED LIKE SMOKE. IT WAS NOT CONSTANT BUT INTERMITTENT. THE DRIVER DECIDED TO STOP TO INVESTIGATE. HE PULLED TO THE EMERGENCY LANE OF I-64 AT EXIT 61, RICHVIEW, IL. HE DISCOVERED A SLOW PRODUCT DRIP FROM THE DRAIN HOLE IN A RING STIFFENER NEAR THE MIDDLE OF THE TANK. HE PLACED A PLASTIC BUCKET TO CATCH THE MATERIAL AND BEGAN MAKING HIS EMERGENCY NOTIFICATIONS. LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED, THE SHIPPER PER THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER, DRIVERS' TERMINAL MANAGER AND THE MILLER SAFETY DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED. ANOTHER TANK TRAILER WAS LOCATED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SITE. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO AID IN TRANSFER OF THE NITRIC FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER AND FOR SITE REMEDIATION. THE NITRIC ACID WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DELIVERY.    THE TANK FAILURE RESULTED WHEN A REPAIRED FAILED. LOOKING AT THE TRAILER FROM THE REAR FACING FORWARD, THE CRACK IS IN A 5 O'CLOCK POSITION, PASSENGER SIDE, 2 INCH CRACK BEHIND THE FIRST RING STIFFENER REAR OF THE MANHOLE.

column168: ON 2/19 AT 9:45 AM., YUKON-KUSKOKWIM HEALTH CORPORATION (YKHC) EMPLOYEE CHRISTOPHER BROUGHT 7 PIECES INTO THE ALASKA AIRLINES OFFICE IN BETHEL, ALASKA INTENDING TO SHIP THEM AS AIR CARGO. THE FIRST 3 PIECES WERE PROCESSED WITHOUT INCIDENT. MR. CHARLES THEN PLACED A RED UN3373 BOX ON THE COUNTER, HANDLE SIDE UP. MR. CHARLES THEN NOTICED THAT THE ORIENTATION ARROWS WERE POINTING SIDEWAYS SO HE ROTATED THE BOX SO THE ARROWS WERE POINTING UP. WHEN ALASK AIRLINES AGENT ROGER NANCE WAS READY TO PUT THE BOX ON THE SCALE TO WEIGHT IT, HE NOTICED THE BOX WAS LEAKING A DARK REDDISH-BROWN LIQUID THAT APPEARED TO BE BLOOD ON THE CARGO COUNTER. THE BOX EXTERIOR WAS INTACT WITH NO SIGN OF ANY DAMAGE. IT SEEMS UNLIKELY THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX WERE CORRECTLY PACKAGED IF SIMPLY ROTATING THE BOX WAS ALL THAT WAS REQUIRED TO CAUSE A SPLIT.    ROGER IMMEDIATELY USED CLOROX WIPES TO CREAT A CONTAINMENT BERM. ROGER AND ALASKA AIRLINES AGENT ALFRED MCCABE BEGAN WIPING UP THE SPILL. IN THE COURSE OF THE CLEAN UP, ROGER'S PROTECTIVE GLOVE RIPPED AND SOME OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL CAME IN CONTACT WITH AN OPEN CUT ON ROGER'S FINGER.    ALL OF THE PIECES WERE THEN EXAMINED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOX HAD LEAKED ON THE FLOOR. AT THAT POINT THE CARGO OFFICE WAS CLOSED. YKHC WAS CONTACTED AND THEY SENT A PERSON TO CLEAN UP THE CARGO OFFICE. THE CLEAN-UP PERSON DISINFECTED THE OFFICE AND TOOK ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WITH HIM. THE CARGO WAS REOPENED AT 1500.     ON 2/20, LORI CHIKOYAK CONTACATED ALASKA AIRLINES AND ADVISED THAT THE LEAKING PACKAGE HAD CONTAINED BLOOD AND OTHER SAMPLES FROM A PREGNANT WOMAN WHO HAD TESTED NEGATIVE FOR INFECTIOUS DISEASES.
column169: REQUIRE SHIPPER TO TENDER SHIPMENTS THAT ARE PROPERLY PACKAGED TO PREVENT SPILLING.    REQUIRE SHIPPER TO OBSERVE ORIENTATION ARROWS WHEN TRANSPORTING AND HANDLING SHIPMENTS.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While making pickups, one  large battery fell over during transit.  As a result approximately 15 gallons of free product were released.  Approximately two gallons escaped the trailer and the remaining thirteen gallons were contained inside of the trailer.  The Pleasanton Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Pleasanton Fire Department personnel deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  Morgan Environmental Services, Inc. of Oakland, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Morgan Environmental Services, Inc. deployed material to neutralize the free liquid and up-righted the battery with assistance from the Pleasanton Fire Department.  The battery was cleaned and left on the trailer pending further instructions.  Morgan Environmental Services, Inc. completed disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: THE FACILITY PREPARED A SHIPMENT OF A TOTAL OF NINE DRUMS THAT WERE SENT TO A TSDF. THERE WERE 3 TYPES OF WASTES BEING SHIPPED; TWO WERE CLASSIFIED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE AND THE THRID AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE. THESE WASTES WERE LISTED ON THE FACILITY'S HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST # 009105341JJK ANS SHIPPED ON FEBRUARY 28TH, 2013.  WHILE AT THE TSDF, AN ANALYSIS WAS PERFORMED AS NORMAL PROCEDURE AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE REGULATORY LEVELS FOR THE TOXICITY CHARACTERISTICS FOR CHROMIUM AND SELENIUM HAD BEEN EXCEEDED. IT INVOLVED FOUR-FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUMS. THE TCLP RESULTS WERE 10.3MG/L AND 1.04MG/L RESPECTIVELY. THE FACILITY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DISCREPANCY ON APRIL 3RD, 2013. THE MANIFEST WAS CORRECTED.
column169: AN INVESTIGATION TOOK PLACE TO FIND OUT WHAT PROCESS THE WASTE HAD ORIGINATED FROM AND IF THERE HAD BEEN ANY CHANGES TO IT. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TANK WAS BEING CLEANED OUT WHICH CAUSED AN INCREASE IN THE CONCENTRATION OF CHROMIUM AND SELENIUM. THE OPERATOR WAS GIVEN TRAINING TO BE AWARE IF THERE ARE ANY CHANGES TO THE CHARACTERISTIC OF A WASTE THAT IS BEING SHIPPED, A NEW PROFILE MUST BE CREATED. THE FACILITY IS IN THE PROCESS OF UPDATING PROFILES THROUGH ANALYTICAL MEANS TO ENSURE PROPER IDENTIFICATION OF CONSTITUENTS PRIOR TO FUTURE SHIPMENTS.    PLEASE NOTE: ALTHOUGH THE WASTE WAS SENT OUT AS NON-HAZARDOUS, THE TYPE OF PACKAGING THAT WAS USED WAS APPROPRIATE TO SHIP HAZARDOUS WASTE IN.    THERE ARE SEVERAL QUESTIONS ON THIS FORM THAT WERE NOT AVAILABLE AND THERFORE WERE LEFT BLANK.

column168: WHILE ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF SULFURIC ACID, THE VALVE OF AN IBC SNAPPED OFF, THIS WAS A NEWER IBC AND A NEW VALVE. IMMEDIATELY UPON THE ONSET OF THE RELEASE, PIG HAZMAT DIKE SOCKS WERE PLACED TO AVOID MITIGATION, PIG PADS WERE ALSO USED TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL. THE SITE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, PH TESTS WERE RUN TO VERIFY NEUTRALIZATION AND THE USED SPILL MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO ALL REGULATIONS.    THE BEST ESTIMATE OF THE TIME WAS APPROXIMATELY 10 - 15 MINUTES.    THE DRIVER ALREADY IS ALL APPROPRAITE PPE WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY USING A PALLET JACK AND A TIE STRAP TO TIP THE IBC SO THE SULFURIC ACID WAS NO LONGER LEAKING FROM THE BROKEN VALVE.
column169: WE INVESTIGATED THE VALVE AND THE IBC, AS WELL AS REVIEWING OUR DELIVERY AND LOADING AND UNLOADING GUIDELINES TO DETERMINE IF DAMAGE COULD HAVE OCCURRED DURING LOADING OR ATTEMPTED UNLOADING OF THE SULFURIC ACID. THE VALVE HAD SIMPLY FAILED AND SNAPPED AT THE BALL VALVE, WE HAVE NEVER HAD THIS OCCUR PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE IBC OR ANY ADDITIONAL PORTION OF THE VALVE.  WE DID A POST ACCIDENT DRIVER INTERVIEW AS WELL AS DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTING, AGAIN TO DETERMINE IN THE INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY ANY GUIDELINE FAILURE OR CHANGES. WE HAVE DETERMINED THAT ALL GUIDELINES WERE APPROPRAITE AND FOLLOWED CORRECTLY.    THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED SIMPLY BY A FAULTY VALVE.    WE ALSO HELD A RETRAINING SESSION ON HAZMAT REPORTING, HAZMAT SPILLS AND LOADING AND UNLOADING GUIDELINES TO ENSURE THAT ALL EMPLOYEES WERE PROPERLY TRAINED.

column168: A TRACTOR TRAILER CONTAINING VARIOUS DRUMS, PAILS, KEGS, BAGS AND BOXES OF PRINTING INKS AND OTHER NON-REGULATED MATERIALS HAD AN ACCIDENT DUE TO BLACK ICE ON THE ROADWAY. THE ACCIDENT CAUSED THE TRAILER LOAD TO SHIFT AND EJECT A TOTAL OF 16 55 GALLON DRUMS, A PALLET OF BAGGED POWDERED PIGMENT, AND 24 1 GALLON CONTAINERS OF RED INK. TWO OF THE 1 GALLON INK CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING AND WERE CONTAINERIZED. SIX OF THE  DRUMS CONTAINING INK WERE ALSO COMPROMISED AND REQUIRED OVERPACKING. MITIGATION EFFORTS INCLUDED EXCAVATING AND OFF-SITE DISPOSAL OF INK-IMPACTED SOIL, AND THE REMOVAL OF INK IMPACTED GROUNDWATER FROM THE EXCAVATED AREAS WHICH HAD FILLED WITH GROUNDWATER. FUTURE EFFORTS WILL INCLUDE A SOIL/GROUNDWATER SAMPLING AND ANALYSIS PROGRAM, AND IMPLEMENTATION OF ADDITIONAL SOIL AND GROUNDWATER REMEDIATION, AS WARRANTED.    WHILE NOT SPECIFICALLY ADDRESSED IN THIS REPORT, APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL ALSO SPILLED FROM THE TRUCK'S SADDLE TANK. THIS SPILL WAS ALSO MITIGATED THROUGH THE EXCAVATION AND OFF-SITE DISPOSAL OF FUEL-IMPACTED SOIL.
column169: THE SPILL WAS DUE PRIMARILY TO ICY ROAD CONDITIONS. TRUCK DRIVERS IN SIMILAR SITUATIONS SHOULD SLOW DOWN TO A SAFE SPEED OR KEEP OFF THE ROAD UNTIL ROAD CONDTIONS IMPROVE.

column168: Harcros Chemicals driver, Dexter Austin, was off-loading full, one-ton containers of chlorine at Bermco Aluminum. Just before sitting one of the full containers on the ground, Dexter noticed what he thought was chlorine vapor coming from the end of the container. He sat it on the ground, then confirmed that it was indeed chlorine. At that point he shut the engine down and reported the leak to Bermco personnel. The leak was said to be on the rim of the container chime.  Bermco personnel then called the Birmingham Fire Dept. The fire dept. responded, evacuated Bermco personnel and set up an Incident Command and Control Zone.  The fire dept. accepted our offer to assist them in the efforts to contain the leak. Ken Trotter and I (Charles Haddock) departed the Bessemer branch and arrived on the scene at approximately 10:30 a.m.  Upon arrival, we met up with the Incident Commander, EMA and Bermco personnel. They were in the process of determining their approach. They sent in a team of three, donned in level A protection and carrying a "B" Kit. They returned saying that the leak was coming from a small crack in the chime and emitting a small amount of vapor and there was nothing in the "B" Kit they could use.  After much discussion as to the next approach, it was decided the team would return with some clamps that might be applied, lead washers that might be driven into the crack and a hammer that might be used to hammer the area closed enough to stop the leak. When the team returned this time, they said they were successful in stopping the leak. They said they had stopped the leak by hammering the cracked area shut.   With this being reported, the Incident Commander sent two of his team members in with chlorine monitors to do air sampling.  They returned and reported that the area was all clear.  At this point, the Incident Commander said that he would allow two Bermco employees and two Harcros employees into the area so that the container could be placed into the chlorine room to be hooked up to their process in order to empty the chlorine out of the container.  However, when we got to the area to proceed with lifting the container onto their forklift so it could be moved, we quickly realized that it was still leaking. There was indeed a two inch crack in the outer edge of the chime leaking chlorine but only in a small, pin-hole amount.  We tried for some time to stop the leak with a hammer but were unsuccessful.  This was reported to the Incident Commander and to Bermco's Safety Dept.  Travis Howard, Operations Manager for Harcros in Muscle shoals, was now at the site. Discussions were made as what would be the best option.  We concluded that we should proceed with a plan that Travis Howard had already started in motion earlier in the day. This was to have the chlorine plant in Muscle Shoals prepare several empty ton containers with a vacuum on them, load them on another boom truck and have another driver bring them to the site so we could transfer t

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT JOB SITE TO UNLOADED PRODUCT INTO EQUIPMENT DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO TURN ON PTO PUMPING SYSTEM. DRIVER REALIZED THAT NOTHING WAS COMING OUT OF HIS FUEL NOZZLE AND WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK. DRIVER SAW THAT FUEL WAS SPILLING UNDERNEATH THE TRUCK. DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PUMPING SYSTEM AND THEN PROCEEDED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE FUEL SPILL RESULTED IN A PUMP HOSE FAILURE. THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL AND BEGAN TO CONTACT THE NECESSARY PERSONNEL REGARDING THE SPILL. THE DRIVER AND ON SITE EMPLOYEES STARTED THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS UNTIL ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SPECIALISTS ARRIVED ON SITE.
column169: ONE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED THE FAILED PUMP HOSE WAS UPGRADED TO A HIGHER RATED PUMP HOSE TO ALLEVIATE ANY FURTHER PROBLEMS.

column168: OUR DELIVERY DRIVER WENT TO THE WRONG HOUSE WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY. HE HOOKED UP TO THE FILL PIPE AND STARTED DISPENSING PRODUCT WHEN HE REALIZED THERE WAS NO WHISTLE HE STOPPED THE DELIVERY. HE LOOKED THROUGH A WINDOW IN THE BASEMENT AND REALIZED THERE WAS NOT A TANK IN THE BASEMENT. THE PROPER PROCEDURE FROM REMOVING OR ABANDONING A HEATING OIL TANK IS TO REMOVE THE TANK AND ALL PIPING CONNECTED TO THE TANK OR IF THE TANK STAYS ON CITE THE FILL PIPE IS TO BE PLUGGED AND ONLY THE VENT REMAINS. OUR DRIVER MADE A VERY BAD MISTAKE GOING TO THE WRONG ADDRESS, BUT IF THE TANK AT 6880 PARKWAY EAST, HARRISBURG, PA WOULD HAVE BEEN PROPERLY REMOVED, THIS ACCIDENT WOULDN'T HAVE OCCURRED.
